ce:section.ce:para:
Based on this, a novel nitrogen-doped carbon quantum dots (CDs) was synthesized by hydrothermal method using L-phenylalanine and formaldehyde as carbon source, urea as nitrogen source and water as solvent. The structure and morphology of the CDs were characterized by Fourier transform infrared spectroscopy (FTIR), transmission electron microscopy (TEM), and laser particle size analyzer (Scheme 1
                     ). Through fluorescence measurement, it is proved that dichromate ion can effectively quench the fluorescence of CDs, and compared with other cations and anions, it has better selectivity and anti-interference ability. Finally, the quenching mechanism of Cr2O7
                     2− on CDs is attributed to the internal filtering effect (IFE).
